• Question 1: What is a CSS selector? Provide examples of element, class, and ID selectors.

- A CSS selector is a pattern used to select HTML elements that you want to style.

1. Element Selector:

- Targets HTML elements by their tag name.
- It styles all elements of that type.
Example:
p {
  color: blue;
}
- This will make all <p> elements’ text blue.

2. Class Selector:

- Starts with a dot (.).
- Used to style one or more elements that share the same class attribute.

Example:
<p class="highlight">This is highlighted text.</p>
<style>
.highlight {
  background-color: yellow;
  color: black;
}
</style>

3. ID Selector:

- Starts with a hash symbol (#).
- Used to style a specific, unique element (each ID should be used only once per page).

Example:
<p id="main">This is the main paragraph.</p>
<style>
#main {
  font-size: 20px;
  color: red;
}
</style>



