• Question 3: What is the difference between internal, external, and inline CSS? Discuss the advantages and disadvantages of each approach.

- CSS can be added to a webpage in three main ways — inline, internal, and external.
Each has its own use cases, benefits, and drawbacks.

1. Inline CSS:

- CSS is written inside an HTML tag using the style attribute.
Example:
<p style="color: blue; font-size: 18px;">This is inline CSS.</p>

Advantages:
- Quick and easy for small changes or testing.
- Styles apply immediately to that element only.
- No need for an external file.

Disadvantages:
- Not reusable (you must repeat styles on every element).
- Makes HTML code messy and hard to maintain.
- Has highest specificity, so can override other styles unintentionally.
- Slower for large projects (lots of repeated code).

2. Internal CSS:

- CSS is written inside a <style> tag within the <head> section of an HTML file.

Example:
<head>
  <style>
    p {
      color: green;
      font-size: 18px;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <p>This is internal CSS.</p>
</body>

Advantages:
- Keeps styles in one place within the same HTML file.
- Easier to maintain than inline CSS.
- Good for small projects or single-page designs.

Disadvantages:
- CSS applies only to that page.
- For multiple pages, you must copy styles into each file.
- Increases page size and load time if used repeatedly.



3. External CSS:

- CSS is written in a separate .css file, linked to the HTML using the <link> tag.

Example:
 HTML file:
<link rel="stylesheet" href="style.css">

style.css file: 
p {
  color: red;
  font-size: 18px;
}

Advantages:
- Best for large websites — one CSS file can style many pages.
- Makes code clean and organized.
- Browser caches CSS, improving load time after the first visit.
- Easy to maintain and update.

Disadvantages:
- Requires an extra HTTP request (may slightly delay initial load).
- If the CSS file fails to load, the page loses all styling.